The paper deals with the computational power of integer-valued random reals, which is a topic that falls under the scope of computational complexity theory (cs.CC). The paper also discusses the interactions between integer-valued randomness and genericity, which is a topic in information theory (cs.IT). The use of martingales and betting strategies suggests a connection to probability theory and stochastic processes, which are topics in discrete mathematics (cs.DS). The paper also touches on game theory (cs.GT) and logic (cs.LO) in its discussion of Turing degrees.
